<Layout title="Risk Management">

<Navbar />

<section class="hero">

<div class="container">

<span class="badge">
ISO 14971 Learning Guide
</span>

<h1>Medical Device Risk Management</h1>

<p>

Risk Management is one of the most important activities in the medical
device life cycle. It ensures that hazards are identified, evaluated,
controlled and continuously monitored to protect patients, users and
other stakeholders.

This page explains the complete Risk Management process based on
ISO 14971:2019 with practical examples.

</p>

<div class="buttons">

<a href="/learn/device-classification" class="secondary">
← Previous
</a>

<a href="/learn/clinical-evaluation" class="primary">
Next →
</a>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>What is Risk Management?</h2>

<p>

Risk Management is a systematic process of identifying hazards,
estimating and evaluating risks, implementing risk control measures,
and monitoring the effectiveness of those controls throughout the
entire life cycle of a medical device.

The internationally accepted standard for medical device risk
management is <strong>ISO 14971:2019</strong>.

</p>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Important Definitions</h2>

<div class="grid">

<div class="card">

<h3>Hazard</h3>

<p>

A potential source of harm.

Example:
Sharp edge on a surgical instrument.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Hazardous Situation</h3>

<p>

Circumstances in which people or property are exposed
to one or more hazards.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Harm</h3>

<p>

Physical injury, damage to health or damage to property.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Risk</h3>

<p>

Combination of probability of occurrence of harm and
severity of that harm.

</p>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>ISO 14971 Risk Management Process</h2>

<div class="timeline">

<div class="step">Risk Management Plan</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">Hazard Identification</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">Risk Analysis</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">Risk Evaluation</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">Risk Control</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">Residual Risk Evaluation</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">Risk Management Report</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">Production & PMS</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Risk Matrix</h2>

<table>

<tr>

<th>Severity</th>

<th>Low Probability</th>

<th>Medium Probability</th>

<th>High Probability</th>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Minor</td>

<td>Low</td>

<td>Low</td>

<td>Medium</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Serious</td>

<td>Medium</td>

<td>High</td>

<td>High</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Critical</td>

<td>High</td>

<td>Very High</td>

<td>Extreme</td>

</tr>

</table>

</div>

</section>
<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Failure Mode and Effects Analysis (FMEA)</h2>

<p>

Failure Mode and Effects Analysis (FMEA) is a proactive risk assessment
tool used to identify potential failures before they occur. It evaluates
the effect of each failure and prioritizes risks so that appropriate
control measures can be implemented.

</p>

<table>

<tr>
<th>Parameter</th>
<th>Description</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Failure Mode</td>
<td>Possible way in which the device may fail</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Cause</td>
<td>Reason for failure</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Effect</td>
<td>Impact on patient or user</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Severity (S)</td>
<td>Impact of failure</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Occurrence (O)</td>
<td>Likelihood of occurrence</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Detection (D)</td>
<td>Ability to detect before failure</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Risk Priority Number</td>
<td>RPN = S × O × D</td>
</tr>

</table>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Fault Tree Analysis (FTA)</h2>

<p>

Fault Tree Analysis is a top-down analytical method used to determine
the root causes of a system failure. Logical gates such as AND and OR
are used to identify combinations of failures leading to a hazardous
event.

</p>

<div class="grid">

<div class="card">

<h3>Advantages</h3>

<ul>

<li>Identifies root causes</li>

<li>Supports preventive actions</li>

<li>Useful for complex systems</li>

<li>Improves product reliability</li>

</ul>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Applications</h3>

<ul>

<li>Implant Design</li>

<li>Medical Software</li>

<li>Sterilization Process</li>

<li>Manufacturing Process</li>

</ul>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Risk Control Measures</h2>

<p>

According to ISO 14971, risks should be controlled following the
hierarchy below.

</p>

<div class="timeline">

<div class="step">

Inherent Safety by Design

</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">

Protective Measures

</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">

Information for Safety (Warnings / IFU)

</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Residual Risk</h2>

<p>

Residual Risk is the remaining risk after all risk control measures have
been implemented.

Manufacturers must evaluate whether the residual risk is acceptable
according to predefined risk acceptance criteria.

</p>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Benefit–Risk Analysis</h2>

<p>

If residual risk cannot be reduced further, manufacturers evaluate
whether the clinical benefits outweigh the remaining risks.

Example:

A hip implant carries risks of infection and loosening, but the clinical
benefit of restoring mobility generally outweighs those risks when
appropriate controls are in place.

</p>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Risk Management File (RMF)</h2>

<div class="grid">

<div class="card">

<h3>Typical Contents</h3>

<ul>

<li>Risk Management Plan</li>

<li>Intended Use</li>

<li>Hazard Identification</li>

<li>Risk Analysis</li>

<li>Risk Evaluation</li>

<li>Risk Control Measures</li>

<li>Verification of Controls</li>

<li>Residual Risk Evaluation</li>

<li>Benefit-Risk Analysis</li>

<li>Risk Management Report</li>

<li>Production & PMS Review</li>

</ul>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Related Standards</h3>

<ul>

<li>ISO 14971</li>

<li>ISO/TR 24971</li>

<li>ISO 13485</li>

<li>IEC 62366</li>

<li>IEC 62304</li>

</ul>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Orthopedic Implant Example</h2>

<table>

<tr>

<th>Hazard</th>

<th>Possible Harm</th>

<th>Risk Control</th>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Implant Loosening</td>

<td>Revision Surgery</td>

<td>Mechanical Testing & Design Validation</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Material Toxicity</td>

<td>Inflammation</td>

<td>ISO 10993 Biocompatibility Testing</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Incorrect Implant Size</td>

<td>Poor Fixation</td>

<td>Comprehensive Surgical IFU & Instrument Verification</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Sterility Failure</td>

<td>Infection</td>

<td>EO / Gamma Sterilization Validation</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Packaging Damage</td>

<td>Loss of Sterility</td>

<td>Packaging Validation & Transportation Testing</td>

</tr>

</table>

</div>

</section>
<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Risk Acceptability Criteria</h2>

<p>

Manufacturers must define objective criteria for determining whether a
risk is acceptable. These criteria should be established before the risk
analysis begins and should align with company policy, applicable
regulations and intended use of the device.

</p>

<table>

<tr>
<th>Risk Level</th>
<th>Decision</th>
<th>Required Action</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Low</td>
<td>Acceptable</td>
<td>No additional control required</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Medium</td>
<td>Acceptable with Justification</td>
<td>Monitor and document</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>High</td>
<td>Not Acceptable</td>
<td>Implement Risk Controls</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Extreme</td>
<td>Unacceptable</td>
<td>Redesign Device Before Release</td>
</tr>

</table>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Example Risk Assessment</h2>

<table>

<tr>

<th>Hazard</th>

<th>Severity</th>

<th>Probability</th>

<th>Initial Risk</th>

<th>Risk Control</th>

<th>Residual Risk</th>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Sharp Implant Edge</td>

<td>High</td>

<td>Medium</td>

<td>High</td>

<td>Design Modification</td>

<td>Low</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Sterility Failure</td>

<td>Critical</td>

<td>Low</td>

<td>High</td>

<td>EO Validation</td>

<td>Low</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Wrong Label</td>

<td>Medium</td>

<td>Medium</td>

<td>Medium</td>

<td>Label Verification</td>

<td>Low</td>

</tr>

</table>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Real Industry Case Study</h2>

<div class="card">

<h3>Total Hip Replacement Implant</h3>

<p>

During design verification, engineers identified the possibility of
implant loosening after long-term implantation.

Risk analysis showed a high severity because revision surgery may be
required.

The following controls were implemented:

</p>

<ul>

<li>Finite Element Analysis (FEA)</li>

<li>Mechanical Fatigue Testing</li>

<li>Improved Surface Coating</li>

<li>Biocompatibility Testing</li>

<li>Packaging Validation</li>

<li>Sterilization Validation</li>

<li>Clinical Evaluation</li>

<li>Post Market Surveillance</li>

</ul>

<p>

After verification and validation, the residual risk was considered
acceptable when compared with the clinical benefits of restoring patient
mobility.

</p>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Common Audit Questions</h2>

<div class="grid">

<div class="card">

<h3>Question 1</h3>

<p>

How are hazards identified during product development?

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Question 2</h3>

<p>

How is Risk Acceptability Criteria established?

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Question 3</h3>

<p>

How are Risk Control Measures verified?

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Question 4</h3>

<p>

How is Residual Risk evaluated?

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Question 5</h3>

<p>

How is Post Market Surveillance linked with Risk Management?

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Question 6</h3>

<p>

When should the Risk Management File be updated?

</p>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="grid">

<div class="card">

<h3>Why is ISO 14971 important?</h3>

<p>

It provides an internationally accepted framework for identifying,
evaluating and controlling medical device risks throughout the product
life cycle.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>What is Residual Risk?</h3>

<p>

Residual Risk is the remaining risk after all control measures have been
implemented.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Is FMEA mandatory?</h3>

<p>

ISO 14971 does not mandate FMEA specifically, but FMEA is one of the
most commonly used risk analysis techniques.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Can Risk Management stop after product launch?</h3>

<p>

No. Risk Management continues throughout production and post-market
surveillance.

</p>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

